distribution function in R

Normal Distribution

generate normal distribution dataset.

rr normal_dataset <- rnorm(200, mean = 24, sd=3)

so this dataset have N=200, mean =24 and sd=3.

rr hist(normal_dataset)

\[\mu = mean\] \[\sigma= standard.deviation\]

\[f(x|\mu,\sigma) = \frac{1}{\sigma \sqrt{2 \pi}}~\exp \left( - \frac{(x - \mu )^2} {2 \sigma^2} \right)\]

rr #prob <- (1/(s * sqrt(2pi))) exp(-((x-mu)^2)/(2s^2)) p_normal_dis <- function(x, mu=0, s=1) { p <- (1/(s sqrt(2pi))) exp(-((x-mu)^2)/(2*s^2)) p }

rr prob <- p_normal_dis(normal_dataset,24,3)

rr y_dnor <- dnorm(normal_dataset, mean = 24, sd=3)

rr plot(normal_dataset, prob, col=‘blue’)

rr plot(normal_dataset, y_dnor, col=‘red’)

rr pnorm(30, mean = 24, sd=3, lower.tail = T)

[1] 0.9772499

rr qnorm(.9772499, 24, 3)

[1] 30

\[Z= \frac{x-\mu}{\sigma}\]

rr z_score <- function(x) { mu <- mean(x) sd <- sd(x) z <- (x-mu)/sd z }

rr z_data <- z_score(normal_dataset)

rr hist(z_data)

rr plot(z_data,prob)

binomial distribution

n trial,
k successes, (with replacement)
fixed probability

\[PMF : {{n}\choose{k}} \cdot p^k(1-p)^{n-k}\]

rr num_flips <- 10 coin <- c(‘head’, ‘tail’) # head 1, tail 0, or success 1, failure 0 flips <- list(sample(coin, size = num_flips, replace = TRUE)) flips

[[1]]
 [1] \head\ \tail\ \head\ \tail\ \tail\ \tail\ \head\ \tail\ \head\ \head\

rr binom_dataset <- rbinom(2000, 10, 0.5)

rr p_dbinom <- dbinom(binom_dataset, 10, .5)

rr plot(binom_dataset, p_dbinom)

link

# Create a sample of 50 numbers which are incremented by 1.
x <- seq(0,50,by = 1)

# Create the binomial distribution.
y <- dbinom(x,50,0.5)

pbinom()

This function gives the cumulative probability of an event. It is a single value representing the probability.

# Probability of getting 26 or less heads from a 51 tosses of a coin.
x <- pbinom(26,51,0.5)

x

qbinom()

This function takes the probability value and gives a number whose cumulative value matches the probability value.

# How many heads will have a probability of 0.25 will come out when a coin
# is tossed 51 times.
x <- qbinom(0.25,51,1/2)
x

This function generates required number of random values of given probability from a given sample.

# Find 8 random values from a sample of 150 with probability of 0.4.
x <- rbinom(8,150,.4)
x

beta distribution

link for parameter calculation

#beta distribution

alpha <- 81
beta <- 219

data_beta <- rbeta(100, alpha, beta)
plot(data_beta, dbeta(data_beta, alpha, beta), col='red')


#new 300 n added. success 100, miss 200
plot(data_beta, dbeta(data_beta, 181, 419), col='green')

estBetaParams <- function(mu, var) {
  alpha <- ((1 - mu) / var - 1 / mu) * mu ^ 2
  beta <- alpha * (1 / mu - 1)
  return(params = list(alpha = alpha, beta = beta))
}
